<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="169" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1436,650,1074]" pageId="18" pageNumber="169">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,974,1001]" pageId="18" pageNumber="169">Comments.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[346,611,975,1001]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Calycomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="169" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stegmaieri">
<emphasis box="[346,611,975,1001]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="169">Calycomyza stegmaieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Esposito" authorityYear="1994" box="[672,834,976,1002]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Calycomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="169" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ipomoensis">
<emphasis box="[672,834,976,1002]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="169">C. ipomoensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are similar in their external morphology and in the shape of their mines, but there are major differences in the aedeagus, with 
<taxonomicName box="[997,1149,1012,1038]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Calycomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="169" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stegmaieri">
<emphasis box="[997,1149,1012,1038]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="169">C. stegmaieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
having a more elongated mesophallus, a smaller distiphallus, and a different shape to the distiphallus tubules.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
